<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI's Okamatsu on Economic Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2312061093 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Dec 
93 Morning Edition -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2312061093 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Received via Nikkei Telecom Database] </F>
  [Text] Jeffrey Garten, U.S. under secretary for 
international trade, who has been here since 20 December to 
attend meetings on automobiles and auto parts in the Japan-U.S. 
comprehensive economic talks, and Sozaburo Okamatsu, deputy 
vice-minister for international trade and industry, gave news 
conferences separately to explain the progress of negotiations 
on 22 December. 
  Both of them reaffirmed the position of wanting to conclude 
the negotiations in the auto sector by the time of the 
Japan-U.S. summit in February. But debate on setting numerical 
targets is still ongoing with no differences in views being 
narrowed. 
  Under Secretary Garten said: "We are not seeking managed 
trade. Nor are we seeking to set the numberical targets as 
objective criteria." But he added, "We need criteria to measure 
the degree of progress made" if trade balance in the auto 
sector, which remains a large factor in Japan's huge trade 
surplus, is to be improved. 
  On the other hand, Okamatsu emphasized once again that Japan 
would continue to reject the setting of numerical targets as a 
way of measuring the degree of foreign products' entry into the 
Japanese market. 
  Regarding the fact that the United States is pressing Japan 
to open its market, citing higher shares which foreign products 
hold in other major nations, Okamatsu insisted that "foreign 
products' share in the United States is not much different from 
their share in Japan" if the products from NAFTA member nations 
are excluded. He thus called on the United States to rethink 
its idea on criteria. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

