<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   FTC Responds to U.S. Unfairness Claims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2712062993 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Dec 
93 Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2712062993 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Fair Trade Commission [FTC] on 22 December 
compiled the results of its survey on business practices by the 
plate glass, auto, auto parts, and paper industries. The United 
States is claiming that these four Japanese industries are 
closed to foreign competition. The survey showed that "they 
have been improving their business practices as can be seen in 
one case in which a company has stopped giving rebates to its 
agent, a practice which can prevent other companies from 
entering the market." 
  The FTC had earlier conducted a similar survey based on an 
agreement reached between Japan and the United States at a 
follow-up meeting held in July, 1992 for the Japanese-U.S. 
Structural Impediments Initiative (SII) talks. The results 
showed that special agents dealt only with commodities from 
certain makers and they were receiving progressive rebates from 
the makers in return for their agreement to set targets for 
business transactions between them. 
  In June 1993, the FTC notified the four previously-mentioned 
industries of problems in their business practices. The recent 
survey was conducted in November and December to see how the 
industries had improved business practices following the warning. 
  The results of the survey apparently show that "each 
industry 
is making sincere efforts to improve its business practices." 
  According to the survey, companies in these four industries 
have taken such measures as abolishing rebates and sending 
messages to agents saying "we do not restrict your freedom to 
deal in the products of rival companies." 
  The FTC plans to "keep watching to see if the industries 
maintain their improvement in business practice." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

