<H3> <TI>   Rally Held in Kadena To Protest Against Crash </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2612130593 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 23 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2612130593 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kadena -- The Okinawa Peace Center and the Labor 
Union of Central Region held a "rally to protest against an 
accident involving FA-18 fighter aircraft" in the morning of 22 
December at a place commonly called "hill overlooking the 
Japan-U.S. Security Treaty" in Kadena-cho. They protested 
against the accident involving U.S. military aircraft and called 
for suspension of flights over residential areas. 
  It was an emergency rally designed to protest against an 
accident involving two FA-18 Hornets from Kadena Air Base [KAB] 
which flew into each other in a training area over the Pacific 
southeast of Okinawa on 17 December. About 60 people, including 
members of the labor union, attended the rally. They expressed 
their feelings by raising their fists at the KAB. 
  At the rally, Yoshimasa Karimata, vice chairman of the Peace 
Center; Kazuo Senaga, vice chairman of the Central Region Labor 
Union; and Seiyu Nakamura, representative of the Joint Struggle 
Council Against Noise, made speeches at the rally. They 
stressed the need to promote daily struggle [nichijoteki na 
tatakai], saying: "We cannot sleep at night because a similar 
accident could happen over land. Danger is always involved in 
the military trainings." 
  Moreover, after Akira Nakane, member of the prefectural 
assembly, and other representatives expressed their resolve, the 
rally adopted a "protest resolution to denounce the FA-18 
aircraft accident and to call for immediate suspension of 
flights by U.S. military aircraft over residential areas." 
Copies of the resolution will be forwarded to the director of 
the Defense Facilities Administration Agency, the U.S. 
ambassador to Japan, and other officials. 

</TEXT>

