<H3> <TI>   Okinawan Town Protests U.S. Forces' Noise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2512064993 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 23 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2512064993 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 22 December, Kadena town assembly members handed 
copies of a resolution protesting against noise caused by 
military training at Kadena Air Base [KAB] to officials of the 
same base, the prefectural government, and the Naha Defense 
Facilities Administration Bureau [DFAB], calling for a reduction 
in noise. 
  Chairman Eiji Miyahira and eight members of the Special 
Committee for Base Affairs visited Ansei Higa, deputy chief of 
the prefectural governor's office, at the prefectural government 
office. They handed Higa a copy of the resolution, which calls 
for, among other things, restrictions on flight time and a ban 
on flights over residential areas in Kadena. 
  The resolution is composed of five requests, including a ban 
on takeoffs and landing, and flights over residential areas 
between 1900 and 0700. Copies of the resolution will also be 
forwarded to Prime Minister Hosokawa, Foreign Minister Hata, 
Defense Agency Director General Aichi, Prefectural Governor Ota, 
the director of the DFAB, and the U.S. ambassador to Japan. 

</TEXT>

