<H3> <TI>   `International Military Source': Nodong-I Mobile </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2512015993 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2512015993 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] It has become clear that the Nodong-I ballistic 
missiles being produced by the DPRK (North Korea) are mobile. 
This was revealed by an international military source on 23 
December. If these missiles are operationally deployed in the 
conditon of being able to be moved around, most likely it will 
become difficult for Japan to intercept them when they are fired 
at this country or for the U.S. armed forces to attack the 
missiles in case of contigencies. The source predicted that the 
Nodong-I missiles will be operationally deployed next year. 
  According to the Defense Agency, North Korea succeeded in 
test-firing a Nodong-I missile into the Sea of Japan in late 
May. At that time, missiles were launched from a fixed 
launching pad on the coast facing the Sea of Japan. As such, it 
was thought that changing missile launching positions would be 
difficult. But the analysis of information carried out by Japan 
and the United States has revealed that the missiles can use 
mobile launching platforms as well. Because the missiles are so 
large, however, it is said that they cannot be launched from a 
sea vessel. 
  The Defense Agency at present assumes the range of the 
Nodong-I to be about 1,000 km, and it has made public the 
results of its analysis which indicate that all of Japan, with 
the exception of only part of Hokkaido, lies within this range. 
  Even when the Nodong-I missiles become mobile, their range 
will not change much, but because they will not use fixed 
missile bases, it is thought that it will be difficult to 
predict from where the missiles will be launched. 
  Furthermore, because North Korea is proceeding to place its 
military facilities underground, a top Defense Agency official 
said, "It will become difficult for the U.S. Armed Forces to 
attack the missile facilities even if they want to." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-46517 </DOCNO>
