<H3> <TI>   Hata: No Change in Plan To Aid Russian Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2212105693 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2212105693 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata issued a statement on 
20 December that victory of communists and ultra-rightists in 
the Russian parliamentary elections does not affect Japanese 
policy to support President Boris Yeltsin's economic reform. 
  Commenting on the landslide victory of the ultra-right 
Liberal Democratic Party led by Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, Hata 
noted "that was partly because the Russian public is very 
frustrated with the present circumstances of the reform process." 
  On that ground, He stressed: "Japan strongly hopes all 
members of the new Russian parliament will demonstrate their 
sense of responsibility to both the Russian public and the 
international community, and further promote the nation's reform 
efforts." In conclusion, he added: "There is absolutely no 
change in Japan's policy to offer appropriate assistance to 
Russia's reform efforts." 

</TEXT>

