<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials on U.S. Stance on Numerical Targets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2212132593 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 12 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2212132593 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The United States has begun to adopt a flexible 
attitude on the issue of setting numerical trade targets. A 
senior Foreign Ministry official on 21 December commented on the 
apparent change in the U.S. stance. 
  He said: "It is a feint operation. There is no change in 
the U.S. belief in the importance of trade results. American 
experts and the media have criticized the way the United States 
has pushed for numerical targets as a way of seeking managed 
trade. The United States is probably shying away from using the 
term numerical targets in the face of this criticism." 
  He continued: "The substance of the U.S. policy of attaching 
more importance to trade results than on the market opening 
process, and of pressing Japan to raise the share of foreign 
goods in the Japanese market to levels comparable with the rest 
of the G-7 nations, remains unchanged." 

</TEXT>

